<div class="container">
    <p>C is a general-purpose, procedural programming language that was developed in the early 1970s by Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs.</p>
    <p>Key features of C include:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Procedural and structured: C follows a procedural programming paradigm, making it suitable for developing system software, application software, and embedded firmware.</li>
        <li>Efficient and fast: C provides low-level access to memory, making it efficient for system programming and development of performance-critical applications.</li>
        <li>Portability: C programs can be compiled to run on various platforms with minimal changes, making it a popular choice for cross-platform development.</li>
        <li>Rich standard library: C provides a rich standard library that includes functions for input/output, string manipulation, memory allocation, and more.</li>
        <li>Wide range of applications: C is used in developing operating systems, device drivers, game engines, embedded systems, and other performance-critical software.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Despite being more complex than modern high-level languages, C remains one of the most widely used programming languages due to its efficiency, flexibility, and close-to-hardware capabilities.</p>
    <p>To get started with C programming, you can use a C compiler such as GCC, Clang, or Microsoft Visual C++. There are also numerous online resources, tutorials, and books available for learning C programming.</p>
